      "line": 18,
      "text": "€ Se gore tot"
    },
    {
      "line": 21,
      "text": "COVER: Three views in Sonoma County, California. The background shot was taken near Sebastopol, in country rich"
    },
    {
      "line": 25,
      "text": "+ with Gravenstein apple orchards and grapevines. Even though this area was first colonized by Russia, it acquired its Russian __"
    },
    {
      "line": 29,
      "text": "name from Yankees in the 1850s - an allusion to the Crimean seaport then under siege. Hessel (middle picture), five miles"
    },
    {
      "line": 30,
      "text": "down the no-longer-existent tracks, was settled by immigrants from an area of the same name in northern Germany. Settled"
    },
    {
      "line": 31,
      "text": "3 here now are fruit growers, horse raisers, cow milkers, and commuters. Guerneville (smallest picture) is a logging, lumbering,"
    },
    {
      "line": 32,
      "text": ": and accordion-playing Russian River resort with nearby gravelly river-terrace vineyards, the home of famous champagne."
    },
    {
      "line": 35,
      "text": "These vistas aren’t majestic, but they do attract the attention of cultural geographers who prefer landscapes with depth and"
    },
    {
      "line": 37,
      "text": "the fine patina that develops from use. This preference is best described by J. B. Jackson in Discovering the Vernacular Landscape"
    },
    {
      "line": 38,
      "text": "(reviewed on p. 10): “The older I grow and the longer I look at landscapes and seek to understand them, the more convinced"
    },
    {
      "line": 39,
      "text": "1 am that their beauty is not simply an aspect but their very essence and that that beauty derives from the human presence.”"
    },
    {
      "line": 42,
      "text": "The cover photos were taken by Don Ryan. -Susan Erkel Ryan"
